{
  "text": "Examples in the literature (e.g. [CITATION_1] Packer et al., 2005; [CITATION_2] suggest that the complexity created by a system's internal structure or by a varying environment (or both) opens up a range of new opportunities for bringing about exclusion, for example by exploiting interference between fluctuating controls and system components or by encouraging the system to 'take over' some of the effort required in exclusion. What are the specific mechanisms driving such behaviour and what other complex interactions exist that might be of advantage in excluding the pathogen? To be able to answer such questions it is essential to have efficient numerical and analytic solution methods that provide insight into the dynamics of exclusion.",
  "citation_candidates": [
